Recorded in the studios of the Library of Congress, Oct. 7, 1954, for later broadcast over radio station WGMS-FM during the intermission of the Oct. 30, 1954, Library of Congress Music Division concert.
Originally recorded under LWO 2323 and renumbered in 2003.

Librarian of Congress L. Quincy Mumford discusses Walt Whitman's Leaves of grass with Whitman scholar Harold W. Blodgett and Roy P. Basler, associate director of the Reference Dept. at the Library of Congress. They also talk about Whitman's life, American democracy, and Whitman's poetry in general.

Poems of land and sea and war
These poems are from Leaves of Grass by Walt Whitman.

I hear America singing -- Pioneers! O pioneers -- Song of the open road -- O captain! My captain -- In cabin'd ships at sea -- Aboard at a ship's helm -- On the beach at night -- The World below the brine -- After the sea-ship -- Beat! Beat! Drums! -- Cavalry crossing a ford -- An army corps on the march -- By the bivouac's fitful flame -- Vigil strange I kept on the field one night -- A march in the ranks hard-prest, and the road unknown -- A sight in camp in the daybreak gray and dim -- Old war dreams.
